In article <tedwards.5.0@techno.src.umd.edu> tedwards@techno.src.umd.edu (Thomas Edwards) writes:
>One can argue that a passphrase is never testimony against yourself,
>but a decrypted message is.  I doubt passphrases are constitutionally
>protected, in reality or in practice.

But you can plausibly claim to have forgotten the pass phrase (people
honestly forgetting their passwords is a common enough problem). If
you haven't written it down, they have no way to get it without your
consent (barring rubber hoses, which clearly are unconstitutional).

